lidarity (i.e. greetings, compliments, apologies) and speech acts that involve face-threatening acts (i.e.complaints, favor-asking, suggestions). In the final section, authors consider applications of speech act research within the context of advertising and business relationships.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aIntercultural communication. 0aSecond language acquisition. 0aSpeech acts (Linguistics). 4aSprechakttheorie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aSpeech act theory.1 aBakary, Waguida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBatal, Mahmoud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeebe, Leslie M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBodman, Jean W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoxer, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarpenter, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark Cummings, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEistenstein Ebsworth, Miriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGass, Susan M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGass, Susan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGeis, Michael L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldschmidt, Myra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, John L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarlow, Linda L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHouck, Noel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.